ying prosperity. And right hero wo want to sincerely thank\nthe people who havo given us their trade and ask them kindly to con\ntinue to do so. Wo aro alBo always In tho market for now customers.\nWo glvo you exactly what you order nnd dollver It Johnny on tho\n.spot and ask thoso who havo not heretofore traded with us to glvo us\na few trial orders.\nWo handle the highest grade groceries that can bo bought on tho\nAmerican market. Wo also glvo what you do not order but what\nyou want that Is Prompt, Polite, Kind and Courteous atteutlon. Wo\nalso guaranteo overy thing oxcopt hen eggs.\nOur grocery Btoro Is kept the cleanest of any store In Ardmoro\nand Is fully guaranteed under the Pure Food Law of Juno 30, 190fi,\nSerial number 379D.\nWo nro hero for business, wo want your grocery ordors, wo de\nvote our entlrotlmotothe grocory business, no frills, no red tnpo but\nJust tho best groceries and tho promptest dellvory nnd tho most\ncourteous attention. Would you like to trndo with a house llko this?\nJust phono 2S0 and wo will do tho rest Wo own our own store, no\nronta to pay.\nThis fitoro Is headquarters for spring chickens, fresh eggs ntul\nJacob Hold's moat products.\nW. .7. BLEDSOE, MANAGER.\niNCE\ncommittee to decide upon a chairman.\nRepresentative Sherman, candidate\nfor vice president, will also take part\nin the conference. Sovoral men aio\nbeing considered for tho chairmanship\nand It Is thought that a dodulto do-c-iclon\nwill be reached.\nI. uke Wright, the now secrotary of\nwar, is a confederate veteran and\ndemocratic In his io!ttlcal views, Ills\nselection Is looked upon as a clc cv\npiece of d'ploniacy which may result\nIn gaining many Taft votes In the\nsouth.\nFew men aro more popular In the\narmy than Luke Wright, and, despite\nthe fact that he was n confederate,\nhis appointment has been unlversilly\ncommended by tho loaders of tho\ngrand army of tho republic and by\nunion veternns generally.\nPolice Court News.\nHuk'hosh has been exceedingly quiet\nIn police clrolos within the past few\nda) s and hut few casos hnvo been\ntried before that tribunal. The court\ntil's 'morning held n short sosslon,\nand sentenced one prostitute, ono for\nassociating with prostitutes, and one\ndrunk.\nA short session will 111 all probabll\nir v be held this afternoon.\nCLEARANCE\nLABOR RIOT\nIN ARKANSAS\nBLOODY BATTLE OCCURRED\nVAN BUREN LAST NIGHT.\nTWO STRIKE BREAKERS HURT\nTrouble Caused By Attempt to Re\nsume Work In Iron Mountain\nRailway Shops at Van Buren\nWith Italian Strike Breakers.\nFort Smith, Ark., .1 imp HO. A\nbloody buttle took place lout night be\ntween striking shopmen, w'.ir wcro\nemploy 1 In the St. IOuIh i. lrcu\nMountain nillwny shops at Van Hiren.\nand Italian strike breakers, who hud\nbeen Imported to take their places.\nTwo of the strike breakers crt\ni shot and seriously wounded.\nA PAINFUL ACCIDENT\nMRS. D. E. ALLEN MET WITH AC\nCIDENT ON NORTH WASHING\nTON STREET TODAY.\nMrs. I). K. Allen met with quite\na pultHnl. Is not serious, accident\nthis morning wulle driving on North\nWashington street, tho animal stepped\nInto a hole In the middle of tho street\nand Jerked Mrs. Allen across tho\naxles and dragged here for some dis\ntance before tho horso was stopped.\nThe Injured lady was taken to her\nhome where medical attention was\nrendered, nnd this afternoon Is get\nting along ns well as could bo possl\nblv exported.\nThe city authorities, or some one\nshould he held responsible for the\ncondtlon of gome if the street, 'ind\na few of the streets should ho given\nsome attention before a damage suit\nis brought against the city.\nCAR SHORTAGE REPORTED\nRENEWED ACTIVITY IN BUSINESS\nCONDITIONS IS BEING FELT\nBY RAILROADS.\nIliisluess has not only regained Its\nnormal condition within the pu?' few\nmonths since tho panic but has shown\nnn unusual activity. Tho u-st Index\nto renewed prosperity Is gathered\nfrom tho railroads who suffer most\nduring hard times or business stagna\ntion. Hut a fow mouths ngo, tho rail\nroads were laying off men by tho\nwholesale to cut expenses on account\nof tho fact that the supply of freight\ncars was more than tho demand, and\nJust at this time hoforo prosperity\nbus begun to move good on Its routo\ntho various railway lines In tho coun\ntry and through this section especial\nly are reporting tho fact that the linos\nhnvo two cars of freight for every\navailable car. This speaks well for\ntho return of prosperity and tho de\nliverance of this country from tho\nthroes of hard tlrnos.\nMoney conditions tn the oast wcro\nnever better nnd It Is generally said\nthat money may bo secured at four\nand live per cont and Is going hog\nging nt that rate, whereas a fow\nmouths ngo money was hard to got\nat eight or ten por cont.\nAll of tho largor railway systems\naro reopening their shops nnd replac\ning tho men at work, and laborers\nfor construction or track work aro\nscarce. In tho mechanical lino tho\nBiipply Is hardly equal to tho demand\nami every branch of mechanics nood\niiion to fill places. This section Is nt\npresent doing considerable building\non account of tho cheapness of build\ning material. Tho hanks report an In\ncrease In deposits from overy source\nTho thrifty times of 100C will not\ncompare with tho times this fall, and\nlabor of every description will bo In\ndemand to such an extent that a\ntramp will bo a thing of tho past.\nBaling Wire.\nYou will find plenty of baling wlro\nat Illvens, Corlin Frensley's.\nLIVE IN SECLUSION\nMEMBERS OF THE CLEVELAND\nFAMILY LEAVh PRINCETON\nFOR SUMMER HOME.\nPrinceton. N. J., June 30 Mrs.\nFrances Cleveland, widow of former\nPresident drover Cleveland, left hero\ntoday for her uniiner home at Tarn\nworth. N II., where she will remain\nwith her children until September.\nMrs Cleveland was ne ompanled by\nthe two children. Ksther and Ulelmrd.\nwho attended the fuiii-.il of th I\nfather.\nCUTS THROAT WITH KNIFE\nMAN AT CHERRYVALE TIRES OF\nLIFE BECAUSE OF SEPARATION\nFROM HIS WIFE.\nChorryvalc, Kan., June 30. Archi\nbald Warren, aged -14, committed sui\ncide here enrly this morning by cut\nting his throat with a Jack knife.\nWarren had recently been separated\nfrom his wife by a teii!irarv decree\nrestraining him from railing upon\nher.\nWRIGHT GOES\nIN TOMORROW\nTAFT WILL TURN OVER WORK OF\nWAR DEPARTMENT.\nTHE LATTER IS VERY BUSY\nGetting Business of His Office In Con\ndition to Turn Over to His Suc\ncessor Taft Hasn't Time to\nTalk Politics.\nWashington. I). C, Juno 30. Tho\nformal transfer of tho war depart\nment from tho administration of Sec\nretary Win. II. Taft to that of Secro\ntary Luko U. Wright, will take place\ntomorrow.\nThe work at tho department will bo\nbrought up to date by Taft before\nhe leaves tho olllco tonight.\nMr. Taft announced today that ho\nwould havo practically no tlmo to\ndiscuss political matters, as ho de\nsired to devote the ontlro day to tho\nwork of tho war department.\nBISHOP POTTER IS DYING\nEND OF NOTED DIVINE'S LIFE IS\nDRAWING NEAR HOPE OF\nRECOVERY ABANDONED.\nCoopertown, N. V., Juno 30. Hlshop\nHenry C. Potter of New York, who Is\nseriously III here. Is not expected to\nlive through tho day.\nHe passed a restless night and to\nday he Is reported very low.\nHe was brought here from Now\nYork last month In tho hope cf bene\nlltlng his health.\nLEAVE HOSPITAL \"TOMORROW\nCONGRESSMAN SHERMAN RAP-\nIDLY RECOVERING FROM\nRECENT ILLNESS.\nCleveland, O., Juno 30. Congress\nman .lames S. Sherman continues to\nImprove.\nHis condition was normal today\nand ho will probably leave tho hos\npital tomorrow.\nHoWltt's I.ittlo Karly Risers, tho\nfamous little liver pills, nro sold by\nW n Frame dft.w\nI\nnu nuiib juui muiiv auu juu u\nbo glad you gave It to us.\nI\nExcelsior Steam Laundry\nv J\nA POLITICAL\nPRISONER SHOT\nSENTINEL IN RUSSIA PRISON j\nFIRES UPON WOMAN.\nWAS DEAD AT FIRST SHOT\nPrison Officials Say Murdered Woman\nWas Signalling to Other Prison\ners With Mirror When Sho\nWas Fired Upon.\nKiev. Russia, June 30 -M.id.utio\nnolle Slierstnowi, contlnc( In the po\nlitical pr.aoii hero, was tdoay shot\nnnd killed by a prison hoiiIIii-I\nThe sentinel claims that ht. caught\nthe woliiHU signalling with a n. ior\nto some co-prisoners, while siundl'n;\nat a window, when he find The shot\nended the woman's life\n\"BUILD NOW\" CAMPAIGN\nBEGUN BY THE AMERICAN LUM\nBERMAN HAVING ITS EFFECT\nIN THHIS CITY.\nOne of the most noteworthy effort\nto mew ,mhiic opinion and to instill\neiiiitlileiiee in tile public mind is now\nbeing made by tho American Lumber\nman of Chicago, tho leading organ\nof the trade. Thin publication has\nslatted u \"llulld Now\" campalgu, urg\ning people all ouir tho country to\nbuild and po.utlug out the saving to\nbe secured by doing so, II gi ires as to\ni he cost of materials now and a year\nago being given. Tho newspapers and\ncommercial clubs throughout tho coun\ntry have been apponlod to and weekly\nbulletins nre being sent out to show\nwhat Is being done and to still further\nenthiiHi- the public. The effect of tills\ncampaign cannot lie otherwise than\n'vouderiul in Its scope and iullueuco\nand Is already beginning to be felt.\nIn a statement furnish d the publi\ncation by tho Ai'dliioio Commercial\nClub the operations in the city and\nvicinity for tint past fow months are\ngone over in detail. It Is pointed out\nttiiit a number of houses aro now tu\ncourse of erection, a number of others\ncontracted for and tho prospects good\nfor busy fall. Tho completion of the\nstrei t railway, the prospective paving,\nthe probable Usiiunco of bonds for\nnumerous city Improvements, the fact\nthat the county will also vote on Is\nsuance of bonds for the building of\na court house and other purposes,\nare all dwelt on emphatically and It\nIs to lie doubted if many cities of\nthe size can point to a prouder rec\nord than Ardmoro at tills time. Aril\ncloH of h similar tenor havo been\nsent other publ'rntlous and iho effects\nof the removal of restrictions lu nl\nwas touched on as this Is one of the\nfeatures of advertising Ardmoro to\ndav which will bring the quickest anil\n;rontoi.i results.\nHEARST LOSES IN RECOUNT\nJUSTICE LAMBERT INSTRUCTS\nJURY TO FIND VERDICT IN\nFAVOR OF McCLELLAN.\nNew York, N. Y., June :;u Jus\ntlcu Lambert today dlroctel ilie jur\nto find ii vordlct for Mayor Oeorge\nII. McCIollau lu the election recount\nsuit, which upholds McClolland's\nelection as mayor.\nIn his address to tho Jury Justice\nLambert wild that no fraud had been\npro. on lu the cuso und It ho should\npermit tho disfranchisement of citi\nzens on such slight evidence, this\ncountry would last hut a short tlmo\nHorn, this morning nt 11 o'clock, a\nson to Mr. und Mrs, John S. Hummer\non west Main street. Tho fath r\nboasts th.v: \"Taft\" was the firs\nword ut( i d by tho youn m r\nYou need to read tho facts before\nmaking an Intelligent decision See\nthe I.audon Conservatory announce-\nmeats fouud lu this Issuo,\n30\nWEDNESDAY\nWe will Sell\nP\nL\nMBR01DERY\nThe li! I a and In grade, nil new, no old stufr. Wednesday Mc\nAll Title Hands, beautiful design, go ednendii ji)L\n7'ic. J I (id Mini J I ,i() r.inliroldor unci Hands, Including those beautiful\nwide tl nun-, s.go Wednesday while they lust Hull I'rli e\nPORSfTS Choleeof our \"Nemo\" and \"American Ileaiitv\"\nW1WL,1 J M.00 Corsets, Wednesday ur,c\nII .50 grade orsets, Wednesday SI.IO\n00 gra le Corsets, Wednesday SIM\nS'.!. .10 grade Cornels, Wednesday $l.(i,t\nLadles' I0o K tilt ests for ,qt\n1000 yards wide Torchon I.aeeand Insertion, lOe value, Wed. 4 l-Jc\nI'M) yar.lt Vnl l.aees, good 5 to He Value, Wednesday Ac\nAll Net Waists, not iniiny to oiler, hut they are ronl swell,\nWednesday (j(f\nHear in mind, our goods aro all now, nothing old, shop worn or\nMoth eaten.\nNi w Models Kuho\nDISTRICT\nCONFERENCE\nOF THE METHODI! CHURCH\nWILL BE HELD MURE.\nAN INTERESTING PROGRAM\nFor the Three Days' Session Has\nBeen Arranged Over 160 Dsle\ngates Will be Hero in At\ntendance at Meeting.\nIleg